ce:section.ce:para:
To prove the applicability of the designed PVA@WTR-CDs composite thin film as a UV blocking material, a small experiment was performed on laboratory scale for grape storage. Here we have used grapes as a model fruit and observed results are as shown in Fig. 9
                     . The experiment was carried out in two sets for period of 30 h under UV lamp. Approximately, the same number of the grapes was placed in paper tea cups namely A, B, and C. The cup A is taken as it is without wrapping of film while the cups B and C were wrapped with the pristine PVA film and PVA@WTR-CDs composite thin film respectively. The above two sets were monitored for the different time interval till 30 h under UV lamp in a UV chamber. There are significant eye observable changes were seen in color and shape of grapes only after the 15 h of exposer to the UV light. The grapes in cup A and cup B were slightly brownish in color as compared to the grapes in cup C. Then UV irradiation is continued up to 30 h and changes were pictorially shown in Fig. 9. The grapes in the cup A and B were more brownish and shrunken as compared to the cup C. The results show that, the grapes wrapped with PVA@WTR-CDs composite film in cup C are intact with the UV light. There were not much noticeable changes were seen in shape, size and color of grapes in cup C. From the above results we can conclude that, PVA@WTR-CDs composite films are one of the next generation UV blocking materials and can be used practically in food packaging and other related applications of UV blocking on large scale. The overall results of PVA@WTR-CDs composite films are also compared with other UV blocking materials (Table 3
                     ).
